"{\"uid\": \"thesouthafrican.com-sport-paris-olympics-2024-novak-djokovic-rafael-nadal-on-blockbuster-paris-olympics-2024-collision-course-breaking-news-result\", \"text\": \"Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.  thesouthafrican.com is a division of Blue Sky Publications Ltd. Reproduction without permission prohibited  Home\\u00bbSport\\u00bbParis Olympics 2024\\u00bbNovak Djokovic, Rafael Nadal on blockbuster Paris Olympics 2024 collision course  Novak Djokovic and Rafael Nadal were placed on a second-round collision course in the draw for the Paris Olympics 2024.  Grand Slam record-breakersNovak DjokovicandRafael Nadalwere placed on a second-round collision coursein the drawfor theParis Olympics 2024on Thursday.  For the latest Paris Olympics 2024 news, bookmarkThe South African website'sdedicated section  Nadal, a singles gold medallist at the 2008 Olympics, is playing in his final Games having also won doubles gold in Rio in 2016 while Djokovic was a bronze medallist in singles in 2008.  Djokovic, a 24-time major winner and top seed in Paris following the withdrawal of world number oneJannik Sinner, begins his campaign against Australia'sMatthew Ebden.  Nadal, who has won 14 of his 22 Grand Slams on the clay of Roland Garros, faces Hungary'sMarton Fucsovicsin his opener.  French Open and Wimbledon championCarlos Alcaraz, the second seed, faces 275th-rankedHady Habibof Lebanon.  Two-time singles gold medallistAndy Murray, who will end his career at the Olympics after almost two decades on tour, will only play doubles.  The 37-year-old former world number one underwent surgery to remove a cyst on his back before Wimbledon, which also sidelined him from singles at the All England Club.  At the Olympics he will play doubles withDan Evans.  \\\"I have taken the decision to withdraw from the singles to concentrate on the doubles with Dan,\\\" Murray said in a statement.  \\\"Our practice has been great and we are playing well together. Really looking forward to getting started and representing GB one more time.\\\"  Also making her last appearance will be Germany'sAngelique Kerber, who announced on Thursday thatshe will retireonce the Games end.  The 36-year-old, who won three Grand Slam titles, was a silver medallist in singles at the 2016 Rio Olympics.  In a first-round clash of mothers, Kerber faces four-time Grand Slam championNaomi Osakaof Japan.  Women's world number oneIga Swiatek, returning to the scene of her fourth French Open title last month, begins against Romania'sIrina-Camelia Begu.  Second-ranked US Open championCoco Gauff, who missed the Tokyo Olympics three years ago with Covid, takes on Australia'sAjla Tomljanovic.  By Garrin Lambley \\u00a9 Agence France-Presse  WIN R2 000: Take The South African's SASSA Survey  The South African is hiring! Freelance writing positions available  Follow The South African on Facebook for the latest local and international news  Follow The South African's WhatsApp channel for the latest sport, lifestyle and local news  Follow The South African on X for the latest, breaking news  A brand new shopping mall is coming to Pretoria East, bringing major retailers and new convenience to the area.  Orlando Pirates are reportedly set to welcome a new staff member in former Stellenbosch FC Head of Recruitment Brendon Fourie.  Masindi Nemtajela was stretched off during Orlando Pirates' 6-0 win over TS Galaxy on Sunday afternoon in Mbombela.  IT support is not just technical, it is personal.  Liema Pantsi's victory was clouded as fans of the 'Big Brother Mzansi' show expressed that Smash Afrika was unprofessional towards her.  A dominant weekend for the SA teams in the URC has made a big impact on the latest log standings as the playoffs edge closer.    TheSouthAfrican.com is all about South Africa and the stories that affect South Africans, wherever they are in the world.  We are independent.No agenda.No bias.  Our offices are for administrative purposes only, no 